<center>
<h1>
The Cookie Technology</h1></center>

<center><img SRC="tbullet.gif" height=19 width=24><b>retrieve cookies with
<font face="Lucida Handwriting"><font color="#993366">Perl</font></font></b></center>

<p><b>#! /usr/bin/perl -w</b>
<p><b>use CGI;</b>
<br><b>use CGI::Cookie;</b>
<p><b>my %cookies = fetch CGI::Cookie;</b>
<br><b>my $cookie = $cookies{ "username" };</b>
<p><b>if ( $cookie eq "" )</b>
<br><b>{</b>
<br><b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; $cookie = "There was no cookie named username!";</b>
<br><b>}</b>
<br><b>else</b>
<br><b>{</b>
<br><b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; $cookie = "Found a cookie name username with
a value of " . $cookie;</b>
<br><b>}</b>
<p><b>print $q->header( -cookie=>$cookie ),</b>
<br><b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; $q->start_html(
'Perl Cookie Example II' ),</b>
<br><b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; $q->p, $cookie,
$q->p,</b>
<br><b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; $q->end_html;</b>
<br>&nbsp;
<p><b><u>Notes</u></b>
<ul>
<li>
<b>As in creation, you may retrieve cookies without using the CGI library.&nbsp;
But then, you have to access cookies via the enviornment variable HTTPD_COOKIE.&nbsp;
The variable is a string that contains all the cookies, separated by semicolons.&nbsp;
To access a specific cookie, you will have to either search through the
string or split the string into separate cookies before accessing them.</b></li>

<li>
<b>The above example lets the CGI library do all the dirty work.</b></li>
</ul>

